WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:11.000
My name is Maya Gans and I am so excited to be co-teaching the workshop Web Design for

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:14.000
Shiny Developers this year at POSIConf 2023.

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:17.000
I'm David, software developer at Novartis.

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:23.000
Today I want to talk to you about the workshop we are going to give with Maya Gans at the

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:25.000
POSIC conference at the end of the year.

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:29.000
There's a lot of reasons why I think this course is important for Shiny developers,

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:32.000
but in this video, I'm going to distill it to my top three.

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:36.000
The first one is self-sufficiency in design.

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:42.000
Most applications, developers work hand in hand with designers to create applications,

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:46.000
but in this course, we're going to give you that autonomy to feel comfortable in your

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:49.000
design decisions and create an app all by yourself.

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:55.000
In this workshop, we'll start from the very beginning, from the user requirements.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:01:00.000
You'll learn how to deal with them and how to translate them into mock-ups.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:08.000
You'll leverage wireframing to, in the end, come up with a solution that satisfies the client.

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:10.000
The second skill is user experience.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:16.000
So, not only will we define what that means, but we'll give you the tips and tricks as

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:21.000
well as tools to make sure that you're talking to your end users and making sure that the

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:25.000
app sparks joy for the people using your app on a daily basis.

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:30.000
In this workshop, you'll learn how to deal with these kind of things.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:36.000
For instance, you'll think for the end users, what do the end users want to see when there

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:37.000
is an error?

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:41.000
What do the end users want to see when there is a computation?

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:46.000
The last and what I think is probably the most important skill that you will get from

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:52.000
this course is that we're going to be teaching these design fundamentals, such as color,

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:58.000
typography, layout, using the nomenclature and code in R.

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:04.000
So, this course is already geared to the language that you know and love, and you will leave

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:06.000
with code ready to go.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:11.000
I'm convinced by the end of the workshop, you will accumulate a lot of different best

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:19.000
practices around web design, so you can quickly determine what is a good UI, what is a bad UI.

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:24.000
And the good UI doesn't matter if you are a good R developer, doesn't matter your level

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:26.000
in Shiny development.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:32.000
It's just about soft skills, so that you can seamlessly translate those skills into your

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:34.000
previous work.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:39.000
Thanks so much for watching this video, and I hope to see you at the conference.

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:41.000
Thank you so much and hope to see you there.

